41-Day Oregon Standoff Ends With Surrender, Arrest Of Final Four Protestors - Worldnews.com

The 41-day standoff at an Oregon wildlife refuge ended Thursday when the four remaining protesters were arrested without incident, multiple news reports said.

The first three protesters surrendered to FBI agents two hours prior to the surrender of the fourth man, Al Jazeera reported.

 
 
 
 
 
 The four protesters were indicted last week, together with 12 others previously arrested on charges of conspiring to impede federal officers during the standoff at the compound.

Protesters took over the Malheur National Wildlife Reserve on Jan. 2 blaming the occupation on the return to prison of two Oregon farmers convicted of setting fires that spread to federal property in the vicinity of the refuge near Bend, Ore.

The wildlife reserve occupation was led by Ammon Bundy, and was also directed as a protest against federal control over millions of acres of public land in western United States.

Bundy and 10 others were arrested in January in Oregon, most of them during a confrontation with the FBI and state police on a snow-covered roadside where a spokesman for the group, Robert "LaVoy" Finicum, was shot dead. A 12th member of the group turned himself in to police in Arizona.
