Three of the last four armed protesters occupying a national wildlife refuge in Oregon surrendered today. The final holdout is vowing to remain at the refuge up until his grievances are heard. Tensions were high at the Malheur National Wildlife Refuge in remote eastern Oregon. The standoff began 41 days ago as a protest over federal land control in the West. The protest was led by Ammon Bundy, the son of Nevada rancher Cliven Bundy. The Bundy\'s have a decades long dispute with the government over federal control of the west.

